sect1.para:
Other then that doing event handling from a separate thread, is mostly simple. You can use an event thread function as follows: void*event_thread_func(void*ctx)
{
while(event_thread_run)
libusb_handle_events(ctx);

returnNULL;
}

Applications which do not use hotplug support, should not start the event thread until after their first call to libusb_open(), and should stop the thread when closing the last open device as follows: voidmy_close_handle(libusb_device_handle*dev_handle)
{
if(open_devs==1)
event_thread_run=0;

libusb_close(dev_handle);//Thiswakesuplibusb_handle_events()

if(open_devs==1)
pthread_join(event_thread);

open_devs--;
}

Applications using hotplug support should start the thread at program init, after having successfully called libusb_hotplug_register_callback(), and should stop the thread at program exit as follows: voidmy_libusb_exit(void)
{
event_thread_run=0;
libusb_hotplug_deregister_callback(ctx,hotplug_cb_handle);//Thiswakesuplibusb_handle_events()
pthread_join(event_thread);
libusb_exit(ctx);
}
